% ============================================================
% Section 1: Introduction
% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Background and Motivation}

The dominance of English as the lingua franca of computer science and software development has created significant barriers for non-English speakers, particularly in the Arab world where over 400 million people speak Arabic as their native language. Despite the rapid growth of technology adoption in Arab countries, the lack of Arabic-first programming tools has resulted in a substantial skills gap that impedes technological innovation and economic development in the region.

The historical development of programming languages has been predominantly Anglo-centric, beginning with languages like FORTRAN, COBOL, and C in the mid-20th century, and continuing through modern languages such as Python, JavaScript, and Rust. While these languages have become industry standards, their English-based syntax inherently privileges native English speakers and creates additional cognitive overhead for speakers of other languages.

This linguistic barrier is particularly pronounced for Arabic speakers due to several unique challenges:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Script Directionality:} \textarabic{العَرَبِيَّة تُكتَب مِن اليَمين إلَى اليَسار (RTL)}
    \item \textbf{Character Set:} Arabic uses a non-Latin alphabet with 28 letters
    \item \textbf{Morphological Complexity:} \textarabic{العَرَبِيَّة لَها نِظام اشتِقاق ثُلاثي}
    \item \textbf{Numerical Systems:} Eastern and Western Arabic numerals
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Previous Attempts at Arabic Programming Languages}

Several attempts have been made to create Arabic programming languages:

\textbf{Al-Ramz (2008):} \textarabic{لُغة تَعلِيمِيَّة بِدون مِيزات حَديثَة}

\textbf{Qalb (2013):} An interpreted language with performance limitations

\textbf{Arabix (2015):} Remained conceptual without implementation

\subsection{Contributions of This Paper}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Native Arabic Syntax:} \textarabic{مُتَغَيِّر، دالَّة، صِنف، إِذا، لِكُل}
    \item \textbf{5-Tier JIT Compilation:} Achieving 5.08x speedup
    \item \textbf{ONNX Integration:} Native ML model deployment
    \item \textbf{Vibe Coding:} \textarabic{البَرمَجَة بِاللُّغةِ الطَّبيعِيَّة}
    \item \textbf{UI Framework:} 30+ Arabic-optimized components
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
% Section 2: Related Work
% ============================================================
\section{Related Work}

\subsection{Non-English Programming Languages}

Wenyan-lang demonstrated Chinese syntax feasibility with 18,000+ GitHub stars. Japanese Dolittle and Russian Rapira showed that localized languages reduce entry barriers. Al-Marjaa targets both educational and production use cases.

\subsection{Natural Language Programming}

GitHub Copilot demonstrates AI-assisted code generation, but primarily operates with English. Al-Marjaa's Vibe Coding enables end-to-end Arabic programming.

\subsection{JIT Compilation Techniques}

PyPy demonstrated 5-10x speedups for Python. Al-Marjaa implements a custom 5-tier JIT compiler achieving comparable performance.

% ============================================================
% Section 3: Language Design
% ============================================================
\section{Language Design}

\subsection{Syntax Principles}

The syntax is designed around three principles: linguistic authenticity, conceptual clarity, and technical feasibility. Table~\ref{tab:keywords} presents core keywords.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Core Language Keywords \textarabic{الكَلِماتُ المِفتاحِيَّة}}
\label{tab:keywords}
\begin{tabular}{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Arabic} & \textbf{Transliteration} & \textbf{English} & \textbf{Category} \\
\midrule
\textarabic{مُتَغَيِّر} & mutaghayyar & variable & Declaration \\
\textarabic{ثابِت} & thabit & constant & Declaration \\
\textarabic{دالَّة} & dallah & function & Declaration \\
\textarabic{صِنف} & sanf & class & Declaration \\
\textarabic{إِذا} & idha & if & Control \\
\textarabic{وَإِلّا} & wa-illa & else & Control \\
\textarabic{لِكُل} & li-kull & for each & Control \\
\textarabic{بَينَما} & baynama & while & Control \\
\textarabic{أَرجِع} & arji' & return & Control \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Code Example}

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Factorial in Al-Marjaa \textarabic{دالَّة المَضرُوب}}]
// dallah mudroub(n) - Factorial function
dallah mudroub(n) {
    idha n <= 1 {
        arji' 1;
    }
    arji' n * mudroub(n - 1);
}
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Object-Oriented Features}

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={OOP Example \textarabic{مِثال البَرمَجَة الكائِنِيَّة}}]
// sanf haywan - Animal class
sanf haywan {
    mutaghayyar al-ism;
    
    dallah haywan(al-ism) {
        hadha.al-ism = al-ism;
    }
    
    dallah sawt() {
        arji' "sawt 'amm";
    }
}
\end{lstlisting}

% ============================================================
% Section 4: Implementation
% ============================================================
\section{Implementation}

\subsection{Compiler Architecture}

Al-Marjaa is implemented in Rust for performance and safety:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Lexer:} $<1$ms per 1000 lines
    \item \textbf{Parser:} $<5$ms per 1000 lines
    \item \textbf{Bytecode:} 50+ opcodes
    \item \textbf{JIT:} 5-tier optimization
    \item \textbf{VM:} Stack-based with parallel GC
\end{itemize}

\subsection{JIT Compiler Architecture}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{JIT Compilation Tiers \textarabic{مُستَويات التَّجميع الفَوري}}
\label{tab:jit}
\begin{tabular}{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Tier} & \textbf{Threshold} & \textbf{Optimizations} & \textbf{Use Case} \\
\midrule
Tier 0 & 0 & None & One-time code \\
Tier 1 & 50 & Direct threading & Warm code \\
Tier 2 & 200 & Constant folding & Hot code \\
Tier 3 & 1000 & SIMD & Very hot code \\
Tier 4 & 5000 & Tracing JIT & Critical paths \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Vibe Coding System}

\textarabic{نِظام البَرمَجَة بِاللُّغةِ الطَّبيعِيَّة يَستَخدِم نَموذَج Qwen 2.5:}

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Vibe Coding Example}]
Input: "create variable name equals Ahmed"
Output: mutaghayyar al-ism = "Ahmed";

Input: "if age greater than 18 print adult"
Output: idha al-'umr > 18 { itibaa("baligh"); }
\end{lstlisting}

